Pulling in the wrangled data and creating the training and testing datasets

avocado_clean <- read.csv("avocado_clean.csv") # 10,140 observations of 306 variables
avocado_ca_2017 <- avocado_clean %>%
                   filter(State == "CALIFORNIA" & year == 2017) %>% 
                   dplyr::select(c("AveragePrice", "Total.Volume", "Total.Bags", "type",
                                   "County", "Population_Estimate_2016", "PCT_LACCESS_POP15",
                                   "GROCPTH16", "SUPERCPTH16", "CONVSPTH16", "SPECSPTH16",
                                   "SNAPSPTH12", "WICSPTH16", "FFRPTH16", "FSRPTH16", 
                                   "PC_FFRSALES12", "PC_FSRSALES12", "PCH_FDPIR_12_15",
                                   "SODATAX_STORES14", "SODATAX_VENDM14", "CHIPSTAX_STORES14",
                                   "CHIPSTAX_VENDM14", "FOOD_TAX14",
                                   "DIRSALES_FARMS12", "PC_DIRSALES07", "VEG_FARMS12",
                                   "FRESHVEG_ACRES12", "ORCHARD_FARMS12", "BERRY_FARMS12",
                                   "SLHOUSE12", "GHVEG_FARMS12", "CSA12", "AGRITRSM_OPS12",
                                   "FARM_TO_SCHOOL15", "PCT_DIABETES_ADULTS13", "RECFACPTH16",
                                   "PCT_NHWHITE10", "PCT_NHBLACK10", "PCT_HISP10", "PCT_NHASIAN10",
                                   "PCT_NHNA10", "PCT_NHPI10", "PCT_65OLDER10", "PCT_18YOUNGER10",
                                   "MEDHHINC15", "POVRATE15", "METRO13", "POPLOSS10"))
# Train and test prediction model using 2017 observations from California 
# 424 observations of 48 variables 
# Pre-selected variables without substantial missingness or correlation from subject matter knowledge
set.seed(101)
sample = sample.split(avocado_ca_2017, SplitRatio = 0.70)
train = subset(avocado_ca_2017, sample == TRUE)
test = subset(avocado_ca_2017, sample == FALSE) 
# Randomly split 2017 California data into 70:30 training and testing datasets

Assessing missing data

## TRAINING DATASET 
sum(is.na(train)) 
## [1] 0
# 0 missing observations in training dataset

## TESTING DATASET 
sum(is.na(test)) 
## [1] 0
# 0 missing observations in testing dataset
xTest <- test %>% dplyr::select(-AveragePrice) 
# Retain all predictors and exclude outcome variable

Running random forest in training dataset

set.seed(150)  
train.model <- randomForest(AveragePrice ~ ., data = train, mtry = 15, nodesize = 10) 
# p/3 = 47 predictors/3 = 15 variables tried at each split
# mtry reduces correlation between trees and improves accuracy
# nodesize refers to the minimum number of observations at each split
train.model
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = AveragePrice ~ ., data = train, mtry = 15,      nodesize = 10) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 15
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 0.0551712
##                     % Var explained: 80.33

Evaluating random forest performance in training and testing datasets

pred.train = predict(train.model, newdata = train)
head(pred.train)
##        1        2        4        5        6        7 
## 1.041708 1.153731 1.149174 1.089408 1.281888 1.150697
plot(pred.train, train$AveragePrice)
abline(0,1) 

# Observed vs. predicted values in 2017 California training dataset 

mean((pred.train - train$AveragePrice)^2) 
## [1] 0.03708294
# MSE = 0.035 in 2017 training dataset
cor.test(as.numeric(pred.train), train$AveragePrice, method = "pearson", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  as.numeric(pred.train) and train$AveragePrice
## t = 45.006, df = 289, p-value < 2.2e-16

##  0.9194011 0.9484507

Identifying important predictors

variable_importance <- importance(train.model) 
tmp <- tibble(feature = rownames(variable_importance),
                  Gini = variable_importance[,1]) %>%
                  arrange(desc(Gini))
kable(tmp[1:10,])
feature Gini
Total.Volume 26.3723675
Total.Bags 21.5609968
type 8.4567967
PCT_NHASIAN10 0.8400420
WICSPTH16 0.7870679
Population_Estimate_2016 0.7366202
FRESHVEG_ACRES12 0.6118868
PCT_HISP10 0.5988517
GHVEG_FARMS12 0.5669822
AGRITRSM_OPS12 0.5122400 
tmp %>% filter(Gini > 0.50) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x = reorder(feature, Gini), y = Gini)) +
        geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
        coord_flip() + xlab("Predictor") +
        theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 8))

pred.2017.ca = predict(train.model, newdata = avocado_ca_2017_full)
plot(as.factor(avocado_ca_2017_full$County), pred.2017.ca)

Extending inference to whole United States in 2017

avocado_clean <- read.csv("avocado_clean.csv") # 10,140 observations of 306 variables
avocado_2017 <- avocado_clean %>%
                filter(year == 2017 & County != "roanoke" & County != "stlouis") %>% 
                dplyr::select(c("AveragePrice", "Total.Volume", "Total.Bags", "type",
                                   "County", "Population_Estimate_2016", "PCT_LACCESS_POP15",

Range of avocado price predictions in US in 2017 by county

avocado_2017_full <- avocado_clean %>%
                     filter(year == 2017 & County != "roanoke" & County != "stlouis") %>% 
                     dplyr::select(-"AveragePrice")
pred.2017 = predict(train.model.us, newdata = avocado_2017_full)
avocado_2017_full %>% ggplot(aes(x = factor(County), y = pred.2017)) + 
                      scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 2.50, 0.25)) + 
                      xlab("US county") + 
                      ylab("Predicted avocado price (US dollars)") + 
                      ggtitle("Distribution of predicted avocado price across US counties") + 
                      geom_boxplot(fill = "lightblue", alpha = 0.8) + 
                      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 12),
                      axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12), plot.title =  element_text(size = 12))
